# Models: Primitives + JSON Meshes

No imported DCC assets (`.gltf`, `.glb`, `.fbx`, `.obj`, `.blend`), no texture atlases, no third-party model files for in-world objects.

Every ship, dock, building, crate, terrain piece, and prop comes from one of two sources:

1. **Godot primitives** composed in GDScript with `StandardMaterial3D`.
2. **In-house JSON meshes** under `resources/data/meshes/` (use category subfolders ‚Äî see `resources/data/README.md`), produced by our own low-poly mesh AI tool, loaded at runtime by `MeshTransformer`.

Both pipelines are first-class. Pick whichever fits the shape.

## Pipeline 1 ‚Äî Primitives

Use for simple boxy or symmetric shapes: docks, crates, bollards, terrain blocks, posts, walls.

```gdscript
var mi   := MeshInstance3D.new()
var mesh := BoxMesh.new()
mesh.size = Vector3(2.0, 0.5, 4.0)
mi.mesh = mesh

var mat := StandardMaterial3D.new()
mat.albedo_color = Color(0.35, 0.28, 0.22)
mat.roughness    = 0.85
mat.metallic     = 0.05
mi.material_override = mat
add_child(mi)
```

Allowed primitives: `BoxMesh`, `CylinderMesh`, `SphereMesh`, `CapsuleMesh`, `PlaneMesh`, `PrismMesh`, `TorusMesh`.

Use `MeshBuilder` in `scripts/core/mesh_builder.gd` for common compound shapes and the standard material factory.

## Pipeline 2 ‚Äî JSON Meshes

Use for anything a primitive composite can't express cleanly: hulls, organic forms, characters, signature props.

JSON files live under `resources/data/meshes/<category>/` and must contain only raw geometry:

```json
{
  "vertices": [x, y, z, x, y, z, ...],
  "indices": [i, i, i, i, i, i, ...]
}
```

- `vertices` ‚Äî flat array of floats, 3 per vertex.
- `indices` ‚Äî flat array of ints, 3 per triangle.
- No normals, no UVs, no per-vertex colour. Normals are generated by `SurfaceTool`. Colour comes from `StandardMaterial3D` applied at load time.

Authored exclusively by our in-house low-poly mesh AI. Do not hand-edit vertex data.

### Loading ‚Äî Always via MeshTransformer

```gdscript
var mt := preload("res://scripts/core/mesh_transformer.gd").new()
add_child(mt)
mt.mesh_data_path = "res://resources/data/meshes/hulls/your_mesh.json"
mt.absolute_scale = 1.0
mt.mesh_color     = Color(0.18, 0.20, 0.22)
```

`MeshBuilder.from_data(vertices, indices, color, ...)` is the lower-level entry if you need to bypass normalisation.

### Multi-Part Models ‚Äî ModelAssembler

Use `ModelAssembler` (`scripts/core/model_assembler.gd`) for models made from multiple JSON mesh parts.
This system is generic. Do not put ship terms, NPC terms, or building terms into the mesh layer.

Assembly JSON files live in `resources/data/models/<category>/`:

```json
{
  "name": "model_name",
  "parts": [
    {
      "name": "main_body",
      "mesh": "part_mesh.json",
      "role": "physics_body",
      "position": [0, 0, 0],
      "rotation_degrees": [0, -90, 0],
      "scale": 1.0,
      "color": [0.005, 0.005, 0.005],
      "roughness": 0.96,
      "metallic": 0.0,
      "collision": "convex"
    }
  ]
}
```

`role` is a free-form generic tag. `ModelAssembler` must not know about boats, houses, docks, NPCs, or any other game-specific type.

## Data Folder Rules

- `resources/data/meshes/` ‚Äî raw `{vertices, indices}` only. Never a `parts` array here.
- `resources/data/models/` ‚Äî `{parts}` arrays only. Parts reference meshes by filename; no inline geometry.

Mixing the two formats in the same folder is not allowed.

## Collision

`MeshTransformer` builds a `ConvexPolygonShape3D` by default. Concave shapes are silently disabled on dynamic bodies in Jolt ‚Äî design meshes to be convex-friendly, or split them into multiple convex pieces.

## What Goes in resources/shaders/

Custom `.gdshader` files for water, fog, outlines, sky, etc. Applied to materials at runtime ‚Äî never imported as texture files.

## UI Is Exempt

2D UI (Control nodes, themes, icons) may use imported assets. This rule applies to the 3D world only.
